{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8618cb9f-1894-498d-a51a-c1193cf84d70","content":"No repo content here — this is a general .NET MAUI troubleshooting question. Here's your plan:\n\n---\n\n## Diagnostic & Fix Plan: .NET MAUI Workloads + Android SDK\n\n### Phase 1 — Diagnose (read-only, safe)\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Which SDKs are installed?\ndotnet --list-sdks\n\n# 2. Which workloads are currently installed, and are any out-of-date?\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 3. What does the build actually say? Capture the full error:\ndotnet build MyApp.sln -v diag > build.log 2>&1\n```\n\nLook for these common error patterns in the log:\n| Error pattern | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `NETSDK1147` / \"workload … is not installed\" | Workload missing for new SDK band |\n| `XA0000` / \"Android SDK not found\" | `ANDROID_HOME` / SDK path mismatch |\n| \"API level XX not installed\" | Specific Android platform missing |\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2 — Fix workloads\n\n`dotnet workload update` **is safe** — it updates workload manifests and packs to match your current SDK version. It does not change your SDK version itself.\n\n```powershell\n# Recommended sequence (run elevated / admin terminal):\n\n# 1. Repair first — reinstalls packs for already-installed workloads\ndotnet workload repair\n\n# 2. Update manifests + packs to match the new SDK band\ndotnet workload update\n\n# 3. Verify MAUI workload specifically\ndotnet workload list\n#    Should show: maui, maui-android, android, etc. — all up-to-date\n```\n\nIf a workload is missing entirely:\n```powershell\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3 — Fix Android SDK\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Confirm ANDROID_HOME is set and points to a valid SDK:\necho $env:ANDROID_HOME          # or check system env vars\ndir \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\platforms\"\n\n# 2. Check which platforms/build-tools are installed:\n& \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --list\n\n# 3. Install whatever the MAUI workload expects (typically):\n& \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" `\n    \"platforms;android-35\" `\n    \"build-tools;35.0.0\" `\n    \"platform-tools\"\n\n# 4. Accept any pending licenses:\n& \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --licenses\n```\n\n> **Tip:** If you installed Android tooling via Visual Studio, `ANDROID_HOME` is typically `C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Android\\android-sdk`. If via `dotnet workload install maui`, it may be under `%LOCALAPPDATA%\\Microsoft\\Android\\Sdk`. Make sure only **one** location is referenced.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4 — Validate\n\n```powershell\ndotnet build MyApp.sln -t:Rebuild\ndotnet build MyApp.sln -f net9.0-android   # (adjust TFM to your version)\n```\n\n### Key takeaways\n\n1. **`dotnet workload update` is safe** — it only syncs workload versions to your SDK; it won't downgrade or change your SDK.\n2. Run **`workload repair`** first to fix corrupted/partial installs before updating.\n3. Android SDK issues are usually a **path mismatch** (`ANDROID_HOME`) or a **missing platform/build-tools** version — both fixable with `sdkmanager`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1d9b6043-5b13-43cd-882a-ff7adbca9622","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development on Windows 10, not something tied to a specific codebase. Let me provide a comprehensive diagnostic and fix plan based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI, workloads, and the Android SDK.","outputTokens":992,"requestId":"0433:343824:12DA9C6:152B8DE:6A027B24"},"id":"b44dce93-58ca-4f4e-88e2-96f8a809068a","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:58:36.079Z","parentId":"b533a84f-dda4-47e0-b57c-b39fcb3badb0"}
